ce:section.ce:para:
Gd-doped CDs were prepared using Gd-DTPA as the gadolinium source and glycine as the surface passivation agent (Scheme 1
                        ). Numerous studies have showed that the crystal formation of CDs undergoes a series of dehydration, polymerization, aromatization, and surface passivation processes. A sufficient amount of glycine in the raw solution, which is critical to the degree of carbonization, is necessary to enhance the formation of the Gd-doped CDs. As shown in the TEM images, the Gd-doped CDs obtained were discrete and quasi-spherical, with an average size of ∼18 nm and relatively narrow size distribution (Fig. 1
                        ). High resolution TEM found low diffraction and no discernible lattice fringes, indicating the amorphous nature of Gd-doped CDs. The as-prepared Gd-doped CDs were highly dispersible and soluble in aqueous solution, maintaining colloidal stability for two weeks without visible precipitation in PBS (Fig. S1D). Nanosight system analysis showed an average particle size was 22 nm, which was slightly larger than the TEM results. It might be because numerous hydrophilic groups on the surface of nanoparticles could increase their hydrodynamic radius in aqueous solution during this period of time (Fig. S1A, B, C).
